  "prompt": "What is genetic drift? What are some types?",
  "response": "Genetic drift is a mechanism of evolution in which random changes occur in the frequency of alleles (gene variants) within a population, typically in small populations. Unlike natural selection, genetic drift is a random process that does not depend on the adaptive value of an allele.\n\nTypes of Genetic Drift:\n\n1. Founder Effect\n- Occurs when a small group of organisms leaves a larger population and establishes a new population\n- The new population's gene pool is less diverse and may have different allele frequencies\n- Example: Isolated human populations with rare genetic disorders\n\n2. Bottleneck Effect\n- Happens when a population experiences a dramatic reduction in size due to a catastrophic event\n- Reduces genetic diversity\n- Some alleles may be lost or become more/less frequent by chance\n- Example: Cheetah populations with low genetic variation\n\n3. Random Sampling Drift\n- Occurs in small populations where random reproduction can significantly alter gene frequencies\n- Each generation's genetic composition can change by chance\n- More pronounced in smaller populations\n\n4. Island Effect\n- Genetic drift in isolated populations with limited gene flow\n- Can lead to unique genetic characteristics\n\n5. Sexual Selection Drift\n- Random changes in allele frequencies due to mate selection patterns\n\nGenetic drift is particularly influential in small populations and can lead to reduced genetic diversity and potential extinction.",
